\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 8. P. amygdaliformis} Vill., {\i Cat. Méth. Jard. Strasb.} 323 (1807) ({\i P. parviflora }Desf., {\i P. nivalis} sensu Lindley, non Jacq.). Shrub or small tree up to 6 m; branches sometimes spiny. Twigs grey, dull, tomentose while young. Leaves 2·5-8 × 1-3 cm, narrowly lanceolate to obovate, usually entire, rarely 3-lobed, with rounded or cuneate base, sparsely hairy when young, papillose beneath at maturity; petiole 2-5 cm. Sepals 5-6 × 1·5 mm, triangular, acuminate. Petals 7-8 × 5-6 mm, elliptical, usually emarginate at apex. Fruit 1·5-3 cm in diameter, usually globose, fulvous; pedicel stout, as long as or slightly longer than fruit; calyx persistent. {\i Dry, rocky places. Mediterranean region, Bulgaria.} Al Bu Co Cr Ga Gr Hs It Ju Sa Si Tu.
\par

