\pard\f0\fs28   {\b 9. P. salvifolia} DC., {\i Prodr.}{\b  2}: 634 (1825) ({\i P. communis} subsp.{\i  salvifolia} (DC.) Gams). Small or medium-sized tree; branches usually spiny. Leaves 4-7 × 2-3·5 cm, lanceolate or elliptical, entire, glabrescent above, grey-tomentose beneath; petiole 2-5 cm. Styles more or less glabrous. Fruit turbinate or pyriform; calyx persistent.{\i  Sunny slopes and dry, open woods. • From Belgium to Greece and Krym.} Au Be Ga Gr Hu Ju Po Rm Rs (K).
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28   Often cultivated, and perhaps only naturalized over part of its range.
\par

